  <h1>Service Level Agreement</h1>
  <p>Last updated: April 14, 2026</p>
</header>

<section>

  <h3>Plain-language summary</h3>
  <p>This SLA explains the uptime we commit to, how we measure it, and the service credits you can claim if we fall short. In short:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>We target <strong>99.9%</strong> monthly uptime for paid plans, and <strong>99.95%</strong> for Enterprise plans with a signed order form.</li>
    <li>If we miss our target in a given calendar month, you can claim a service credit on a sliding scale (up to 50% of that month's fees).</li>
    <li>Claims are submitted by email within 30 days of the incident. We'll review and apply credits to your next invoice.</li>
    <li>This SLA applies only to paid plans. Free plans are provided as-is.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>This SLA forms part of our <a href="/legal/terms">Terms of Use</a>. Capitalized terms not defined here have the meanings given in the Terms.</p>

  <h3>1. Uptime commitment</h3>

  <p>During each calendar month of your paid subscription, we will make the Service available in accordance with the following targets:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Plan</th>
        <th>Monthly Uptime Target</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Scale, Growth, and other paid self-serve plans</td>
        <td>99.9%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Enterprise plans (with signed order form)</td>
        <td>99.95%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Free, trial, beta, and evaluation plans</td>
        <td>No SLA (best effort)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>2. How we measure uptime</h3>

  <p><strong>Monthly Uptime Percentage</strong> for a calendar month is calculated as:</p>

  <p><em>((Total minutes in the month − Downtime minutes) ÷ Total minutes in the month) × 100</em></p>

  <p><strong>Downtime</strong> means a period of one or more minutes during which the core Service (the web application at <code>oneuptime.com</code> and the API) is unavailable for the majority of our customers, as determined by our external monitoring. Downtime is measured from the moment we confirm the issue until the Service is restored.</p>

  <p>The following are <strong>not</strong> counted as Downtime:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Scheduled maintenance announced at least 48 hours in advance on <a href="https://status.oneuptime.com">status.oneuptime.com</a>. We aim to keep scheduled maintenance under 4 hours per calendar month and to perform it during off-peak hours.</li>
    <li>Emergency maintenance to address a security or stability risk, where we notify affected customers as soon as reasonably practical.</li>
    <li>Unavailability caused by factors outside our reasonable control, including internet failures outside our network, attacks on your infrastructure, or force majeure events described in the Terms.</li>
    <li>Unavailability caused by your equipment, software, configuration, or network, or by third-party services you have connected to the Service.</li>
    <li>Suspension or termination of your account for cause under the Terms.</li>
    <li>Beta or preview features clearly marked as such.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>We publish real-time and historical uptime at <a href="https://status.oneuptime.com">status.oneuptime.com</a>.</p>

  <h3>3. Service credits</h3>

  <p>If we miss the applicable Monthly Uptime Target in a calendar month, you are eligible for a service credit calculated as a percentage of the fees paid for the affected Service for that month:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Monthly Uptime Percentage</th>
        <th>Service Credit</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Below target, but ≥ 99.0%</td>
        <td>10% of monthly fees</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>≥ 95.0%, but &lt; 99.0%</td>
        <td>25% of monthly fees</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>&lt; 95.0%</td>
        <td>50% of monthly fees</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>Service credits are calculated on the monthly fees for the affected Service (for annual subscriptions, monthly fees are 1/12 of the annual amount) and are applied to your next invoice. If you are on a final billing cycle, we will refund the credit amount to your original payment method.</p>

  <h3>4. How to claim a credit</h3>

  <p>To request a service credit, email <a href="mailto:support@oneuptime.com">support@oneuptime.com</a> within <strong>30 days</strong> of the end of the month in which the Downtime occurred. Please include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Your account ID or the email on the account.</li>
    <li>The dates and approximate times the Service was unavailable.</li>
    <li>Any logs, screenshots, or third-party monitoring reports that may help us verify the incident (optional but helpful).</li>
  </ul>

  <p>We will acknowledge your request within 5 business days and issue the credit within 30 days of validating the claim. You don't need a specific subject line — a plain-language email is fine.</p>

  <h3>5. Support response times</h3>

  <p>For paid plans, we target the following first-response times during business hours (Mon–Fri, 9:00–18:00 UTC, excluding public holidays). Enterprise plans with 24/7 support override these targets where specified in the order form.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Severity</th>
        <th>Description</th>
        <th>Target first response</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>P1 — Critical</td>
        <td>Service is fully unavailable or a security incident is in progress.</td>
        <td>1 hour (24/7)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>P2 — High</td>
        <td>Major feature broken; no reasonable workaround.</td>
        <td>4 business hours</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>P3 — Normal</td>
        <td>Minor feature broken or general question.</td>
        <td>1 business day</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>P4 — Low</td>
        <td>Feature request, documentation question.</td>
        <td>3 business days</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>Support response targets are goals, not guaranteed credits. If we consistently miss them for your account, please escalate to <a href="mailto:support@oneuptime.com">support@oneuptime.com</a> and we'll work with you directly.</p>

  <h3>6. Sole remedy</h3>

  <p>The service credits described in Section 3 are your sole and exclusive remedy under this SLA for any failure by us to meet the uptime targets. Nothing in this SLA limits our obligations under the Terms, your statutory rights, or any additional commitments in a signed order form.</p>

  <h3>7. Changes to this SLA</h3>

  <p>We may update this SLA from time to time. For material changes that reduce your rights (for example, lowering the uptime target or reducing credit percentages), we will give at least 30 days' advance notice by email to the address on your account, and the change will take effect only at your next renewal. Non-material changes (typos, clarifications, or changes that improve your rights) may take effect immediately upon posting.</p>

  <h3>8. Questions</h3>

  <p>Questions about this SLA or a specific incident? Please reach out:</p>
